# Ways of Working: {{ display_name }}

## Definition of Done

A change is considered done when:

- [ ] Code or content passes all lint checks
- [ ] The production build completes without errors or warnings
- [ ] New pages have the required frontmatter (see [content-guide.md](content-guide.md))
- [ ] Images are optimised and have descriptive alt text
- [ ] Lighthouse scores remain at or above the performance budget
- [ ] The change has been reviewed by at least one team member
- [ ] Documentation is updated if the change affects structure or conventions

## Branching Strategy

We use **trunk-based development** with short-lived branches.

### Branch Naming

```
content/<description>       # New or updated content
feat/<description>          # New site features or components
fix/<description>           # Bug fixes
chore/<description>         # Dependency updates, build config
docs/<description>          # Internal documentation changes
```

### Workflow

1. Branch from `main`
2. Make focused changes (content or code - avoid mixing both in one PR)
3. Open a pull request early (draft if still in progress)
4. Request review when ready
5. Squash-merge into `main`
6. Delete the branch after merge

## Pull Request Conventions

### Separating Content from Code

Keep content changes and code changes in separate pull requests where possible. This makes reviews faster and rollbacks cleaner.

| PR type | What it contains |
|---------|-----------------|
| `content/` | Markdown files, images, frontmatter changes |
| `feat/` | New components, layouts, pages, or framework config |
| `fix/` | Bug fixes to components or build config |
| `chore/` | Dependency updates, CI changes |

### PR Title Format

Use conventional commit format:

```
content(blog): add post on performance optimisation
feat(components): add callout component with warning and info variants
fix(nav): correct active link detection on nested routes
chore(deps): update astro to v4.5
```

### PR Description

Every PR should include:

- **What**: brief summary of the change
- **Why**: motivation or ticket reference
- **Preview**: link to the deploy preview (auto-generated by {{ deploy_target }})
- **Screenshots**: before/after for visual changes

### Review Expectations

- Review within 1 business day
- For content PRs: focus on accuracy, clarity, and SEO checklist compliance
- For code PRs: focus on correctness, performance impact, and accessibility
- Approve with minor comments rather than blocking on trivial style issues

## Content Workflow

### Writing New Content

1. Create a new file in the appropriate `src/content/` subdirectory
2. Add all required frontmatter fields (see [content-guide.md](content-guide.md))
3. Write content in Markdown
4. Add and optimise images (see image guidelines below)
5. Run `npm run dev` to preview locally
6. Open a PR

### Updating Existing Content

- Correct errors directly in the relevant file
- Update the `lastModified` frontmatter field if the content substantially changes
- If an article is moved or renamed, add a redirect from the old URL

### Removing Content

- Do not delete pages that may have inbound links without adding a redirect
- Set `draft: true` for content that should be hidden but preserved
- For permanent removal, add a 301 redirect in the framework config

## SEO Checklist

Every published page must satisfy:

- [ ] Unique `title` (50-60 characters, includes the primary keyword)
- [ ] `description` meta tag (120-160 characters, summarises the page)
- [ ] Canonical URL set correctly
- [ ] Open Graph `og:title`, `og:description`, and `og:image` set
- [ ] `og:image` is at least 1200x630px
- [ ] Headings follow a logical hierarchy (one `<h1>` per page, no skipped levels)
- [ ] All images have descriptive `alt` text
- [ ] Internal links use descriptive anchor text (not "click here")
- [ ] Page is included in the sitemap (`sitemap.xml`)
- [ ] No broken links (verified by the CI link checker)

{% if use_i18n %}
For localised pages, also check:
- [ ] `hreflang` tags are correct for all locale variants
- [ ] The `lang` attribute on `<html>` matches the page locale
- [ ] Content is fully translated (no mixed-language pages)
{% endif %}

## Accessibility Requirements

All pages must meet **WCAG 2.1 AA**. Key requirements:

### Colour and Contrast

- Body text: minimum 4.5:1 contrast ratio against background
- Large text (18pt+ or 14pt bold): minimum 3:1 contrast ratio
- Interactive elements (focus rings, links): minimum 3:1 against adjacent colours
- Never rely on colour alone to convey information

### Keyboard Navigation

- All interactive elements are reachable by keyboard (`Tab` / `Shift+Tab`)
- Focus order follows the visual reading order
- Focus is always visible (no `outline: none` without a custom focus style)
- Skip navigation link at the start of every page

### Screen Readers

- All images have meaningful `alt` text (empty `alt=""` for decorative images)
- Icon-only buttons have `aria-label`
- Navigation landmarks: `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<header>`, `<footer>`
- Tables have `<caption>` and appropriate `<th scope>`
- Form inputs have associated `<label>` elements

### Motion

- Animations respect `prefers-reduced-motion: reduce`
- No content that flashes more than 3 times per second

## Image Optimisation

### Format and Size

- Use WebP as the primary format (AVIF for hero images if browser support allows)
- Provide fallback formats via `<picture>` or the framework's image component
- Maximum width: 1600px for full-bleed images, 800px for content images
- Maximum file size before processing: 2MB (the build pipeline will further optimise)

### Responsive Images

Always use the framework's image component (not bare `<img>` tags) for images in `src/assets/`. This ensures:
- Multiple sizes are generated for `srcset`
- Correct `width` and `height` are set (prevents layout shift)
- Lazy loading is applied to below-the-fold images

### Alt Text Guidelines

- Describe what the image shows, not what it is ("A bar chart showing Q3 revenue by region", not "chart.png")
- For images that contain important text, include that text in the alt attribute
- For logos, use the organisation name: `alt="{{ display_name }} logo"`
- For purely decorative images, use `alt=""`

## Performance Budget

Target Lighthouse scores for every page (measured on a simulated mid-range mobile device):

| Metric | Target |
|--------|--------|
| Performance | >= 90 |
| Accessibility | 100 |
| Best Practices | >= 95 |
| SEO | 100 |
| LCP (Largest Contentful Paint) | < 2.5s |
| CLS (Cumulative Layout Shift) | < 0.1 |
| FID / INP | < 200ms |

Performance is checked in CI using Lighthouse CI. PRs that regress scores by more than 5 points should be investigated before merging.

### Common Performance Pitfalls

- Loading large JavaScript bundles for content that could be static HTML
- Unoptimised images (wrong format, wrong size, no lazy loading)
- Render-blocking third-party scripts (use `async`/`defer` and load analytics last)
- Web fonts without `font-display: swap`
- Missing `width` and `height` on images (causes layout shift)

## Architecture Decision Records (ADRs)

We document significant decisions in `docs/adrs/`.

### When to Write an ADR

- Choosing or changing the framework or build tool
- Adopting a new content structure or CMS
- Introducing a new third-party dependency
- Choosing between multiple valid technical approaches
- Establishing a new convention that everyone must follow

### ADR Format

```markdown
# ADR-NNNN: Title

## Status
Proposed | Accepted | Deprecated | Superseded

## Context
What is the problem or situation?

## Decision
What did we decide?

## Consequences
What are the trade-offs and risks?
```

## AI Collaboration Guidelines

{% if ai_context %}
This project is designed for AI-assisted development. The `AI_CONTEXT.md` file provides structured guidance for AI agents.

### For AI Agents

- Read `AI_CONTEXT.md` before starting any work
- Follow the component and content patterns described there
- Check `docs/content-guide.md` before adding or modifying content
- Ensure all images have proper alt text and are using the framework's image component
- Verify Lighthouse-relevant attributes (width, height, alt, lazy loading) on all image changes
- Write commit messages in conventional commit format

### For Developers Working with AI

- Provide clear, scoped instructions referencing specific files
- Review AI-generated content against the SEO and accessibility checklists
- Review AI-generated components for performance anti-patterns
- Update `AI_CONTEXT.md` when component patterns or conventions change
{% else %}
When using AI coding assistants:

- Share the content guide and SEO checklist for content tasks
- Review generated content for accuracy and brand voice
- Verify accessibility attributes on generated component code
- Check performance implications of suggested code changes
{% endif %}

## Communication

- Prefer async communication (PRs, comments, docs) over sync meetings
- Content decisions (tone, structure) belong in the content guide
- Technical decisions belong in ADRs
- Use PR descriptions to communicate context reviewers need
